sec.p:
Let X denote a continuous random variable representing the log-returns of the exchange rate of Bitcoin. Let f(x) denote the probability density function (pdf) of X. Let F(x) denote the cumulative distribution function (cdf) of X. We suppose X follows one of fifteen possible distributions, the most popular parametric distributions used in finance. They are specified as follows:
the normal distribution [41], [42] with f ( x ) = 1 2 π σ exp { - ( x - μ ) 2 2 σ 2 } for −∞ < x < ∞, −∞ < μ < ∞ and σ > 0;
the Student’s t distribution [43] with f(x)=K(ν)σ[ 1+(x−μ)2σ2ν ]−(1+ν)/2 for −∞ < x < ∞, −∞ < μ < ∞, σ > 0 and ν > 0, where K ( ν ) = ν B ( ν / 2 , 1 / 2 ) and B(⋅, ⋅) denotes the beta function defined by B ( a , b ) = ∫ 0 1 t a - 1 ( 1 - t ) b - 1 d t ;
the logistic distribution with f(x)=1σexp(−x−μσ){ 1+exp(−x−μσ) }−2 for −∞ < x < ∞, −∞ < μ < ∞ and σ > 0;
the Laplace distribution [44] with f ( x ) = 1 2 σ exp ( - ∣ x - μ ∣ σ ) for −∞ < x < ∞, −∞ < μ < ∞ and σ > 0;
the exponential power distribution [45] with f(x)=β2σΓ(1/β)exp{ −(| x−μ |σ)β } for −∞ < x < ∞, −∞ < μ < ∞, σ > 0 and β > 0, where Γ(⋅) denotes the gamma function defined by Γ ( a ) = ∫ 0 ∞ t a - 1 exp ( - t ) d t ;
the skew normal distribution [46] with f ( x ) = 2 σ ϕ ( x - μ σ ) Φ ( λ x - μ σ ) for −∞ < x < ∞, −∞ < μ < ∞, −∞ < λ < ∞ and σ > 0, where ϕ(⋅) and Φ(⋅) denote, respectively, the pdf and the cdf of the standard normal distribution;
the skew t distribution [47] with f(x)=K(ν)σ[ 1+(x−μ)2σ2ν ]−(1+ν)/2+2K2(ν)λ(x−μ)σ22F1(12,1+ν2;32;−λ2(x−μ)2σ2ν) for −∞ < x < ∞, −∞ < μ < ∞, −∞ < λ < ∞, σ > 0 and ν > 0, where 2F1(a, b; c; x) denotes the Gauss hypergeometric function defined by 2F1(a,b;c;x)=∑k=0∞(a)k(b)k(c)kxkk!, where (e)k = e(e + 1)⋯(e + k − 1) denotes the ascending factorial;
the generalized t distribution [48] with f(x)=τ2σν1/νB(ν,1/τ)[ 1+1ν| x−μσ |τ ]−(ν+1/τ) for −∞ < x < ∞, −∞ < μ < ∞, σ > 0, ν > 0 and τ > 0;
the skewed exponential power distribution [49] with f(x)=C{exp{ −1p[ μ−x2σα ]p },ifx≤μ,exp{ −1p[ x−μ2σ(1−α) ]p },ifx>μ for −∞ < x < ∞, −∞ < μ < ∞, α > 0, σ > 0 and p > 0, where C = 1/[2σA0 (p)] and A0(x) = x(1/x)−1Γ(1/x);
the asymmetric exponential power distribution [49] with f(x)=C{exp{ −1p1[ μ−x2σα ]p1 },ifx≤μ,exp{ −1p2[ x−μ2σ(1−α) ]p2 },ifx>μ for −∞ < x < ∞, −∞ < μ < ∞, σ > 0, α > 0, p1 > 0 and p2 > 0, where C is given by C = 1 2 σ α A 0 ( p 1 ) + 2 σ ( 1 - α ) A 0 ( p 2 ) ;
the skewed Student’s t distribution [50] with f(x)=K(ν)σ{{ 1+1ν[ x−μ2σα ]2 }−ν+12,ifx≤μ,{ 1+1ν[ x−μ2σ(1−α) ]2 }−ν+12,ifx>μ for −∞ < x < ∞, −∞ < μ < ∞, 0 < α < 1 and ν > 0;
the asymmetric Student’s t distribution [50] with f(x)=1σ{αα*K(ν1){ 1+1ν1[ x−μ2σα* ]2 }−ν1+12,ifx≤μ,1−α1−α*K(ν2){ 1+1ν2[ x−μ2σ(1−α*) ]2 }−ν2+12,ifx>μ for −∞ < x < ∞, −∞ < μ < ∞, 0 < α < 1, ν1 > 0 and ν2 > 0, where α * = α K ( ν 1 ) α K ( ν 1 ) + ( 1 - α ) K ( ν 2 ) ;
the normal inverse gamma distribution [51] with f(x)=(γ/δ)λα2πK−1/2(δγ)[ δ2+(x−μ)2 ]−1K−1(αδ2+(x−μ)2) for −∞ < x < ∞, −∞ < μ < ∞, δ > 0, α > 0 and β > 0, where γ = α 2 − β 2 and Kν(⋅) denotes the modified Bessel function of the second kind of order ν defined by K ν ( x ) = { π csc ( π ν ) 2 [ I - ν ( x ) - I ν ( x ) ] , if ν ∉ Z , lim μ → ν K μ ( x ) , if ν ∈ Z , where Iν(⋅) denotes the modified Bessel function of the first kind of order ν defined by Iν(x)=∑k=0∞1Γ(k+ν+1)k!(x2)2k+ν;
the hyperbolic distribution [51] with f(x)=(γ/δ)λα−1/22πK1(δγ)[ δ2+(x−μ)2 ]1/2K1/2(αδ2+(x−μ)2) for −∞ < x < ∞, −∞ < μ < ∞, δ > 0, α > 0 and β > 0, where γ = α 2 − β 2;
the generalized hyperbolic distribution [51] with f(x)=(γ/δ)λα1/2−λ2πKλ(δγ)[ δ2+(x−μ)2 ]λ−1/2Kλ−1/2(αδ2+(x−μ)2) for −∞ < x < ∞, −∞ < μ < ∞, −∞ < λ < ∞, δ > 0, α > 0 and β > 0, where γ = α 2 − β 2. Several of these distributions are nested: the normal distribution is the limiting case of the Student’s t distribution as ν → ∞; the normal distribution is the particular case of the exponential power distribution for β = 2; the Laplace distribution is the particular case of the exponential power distribution for β = 1; the normal distribution is the particular case of the skew normal distribution for λ = 0; the Student’s t distribution is the particular case of the skew t distribution for λ = 0; the exponential power distribution is the particular case of the skewed exponential power distribution for α = 1/2; the Student’s t distribution is the particular case of the generalized t distribution for τ = 2; the skewed exponential power distribution is the particular case of the asymmetric exponential power distribution for p1 = p2; the Student’s t distribution is the particular case of the skewed Student’s t distribution for α = 1/2; the skewed Student’s t distribution is the particular case of the asymmetric Student’s t distribution for ν1 = ν2; the skewed exponential power distribution is the particular case of the asymmetric exponential power distribution for p1 = p2; the normal inverse gamma distribution is the particular case of the generalized hyperbolic distribution for λ = −1/2; the hyperbolic distribution is the particular case of the generalized hyperbolic distribution for λ = 1; and so on.

Many of the fitted distributions are not nested. Discrimination among them was performed using various criteria:


the Akaike information criterion due to [53] defined by
AIC = 2 k - 2 ln L( Θ ^ ) ;

the Bayesian information criterion due to [54] defined by
BIC = k ln n - 2 ln L ( Θ ^ ) ;

the consistent Akaike information criterion (CAIC) due to [55] defined by
CAIC = - 2 ln L( Θ ^ ) + k( ln n + 1 ) ;

the corrected Akaike information criterion (AICc) [56] defined by
AICc = AIC + 2 k ( k + 1 ) n - k - 1 ;

the Hannan-Quinn criterion [57] defined by
HQC = - 2 ln L( Θ ^ ) + 2 k ln ln n ;

the Kolmogorov-Smirnov statistic [58], [59] defined by
KS = sup x | 1 n ∑ i = 1 n I { x i ≤ x } - F ^ ( x ) | ,
where I{⋅} denotes the indicator function and F ^ ( ⋅ ) the maximum likelihood estimate of F(x);

the Anderson-Darling statistic [60] defined by
AD = - n - ∑ i = 1 n { ln F ^ ( x ( i ) ) + ln [ 1 - F ^ ( x ( n + 1 - i ) ) ] } ,
where x(1) ≤ x(2) ≤ ⋯ ≤ x(n) are the observed data arranged in increasing order.
The smaller the values of these criteria the better the fit. For more discussion on these criteria, see [61] and [62].

An out of sample performance of these risk measures can be assessed by a backtest measure due to [64]:
1 2 τ α | ∑ x i ∈ z α [ x i - ES ^ α ] | + 1 2 δ α | ∑ x i ∈ ζ α [ x i - ES ^ α ] | , (1)
where
δ α = ∑ i = 1 n I { x i - ES ^ α < q α }
for α small,
δ α = ∑ i = 1 n I { x i - ES ^ α > q α }
for α larger,
ζ α = { x i : x i - ES ^ α < q α }
for α small,
ζ α = { x i : x i - ES ^ α > q α }
for α large,
z α = { x i : x i < VaR ^ α }
for α small,
z α = { x i : x i > VaR ^ α }
for α large, and qα is the αth empirical quantile of { x i − ES ^ α , i = 1 , 2 , … , n }. Smaller backtest measures correspond to better forecasting.
